{"add":{"doc":{"id":"1f7afa3b28156e1aa924839496a1b88a9d85dd2d544f0e4d3a0d60f23e278bea","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Tengeru_market.jpg/220px-Tengeru_market.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Trade is the voluntary exchange of goods and services, and is a form of economics. A mechanism that allows trade is called a market. Modern traders instead generally negotiate through a medium of exchange, such as money. As a result, buying can be separated from selling, or earning. Because of specialization and division of labor, most people concentrate on a small aspect of manufacturing or service, trading their labor for products. Trade exists between regions because different regions have an absolute or comparative advantage in the production of some tradable commodity, or because different regions' size allows for the benefits of mass production."]}}}